In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to narrow the type of a value to a more specific type, even if the compiler doesn't know for sure that the value will always have that type. This is known as type narrowing.

Here's an example:
```
let value: any = "hello";

// Narrow the type of value to string
let valueAsString: string = value as string;

// The narrowed type will be used in the rest of the code
console.log(valueAsString.length); // this will not throw a runtime error
```
In this example, we know that the `value` variable will only ever contain a string, so we use the `as` keyword to narrow the type of `value` to `string`. This tells the TypeScript compiler to assume that `value` is of type `string`, even though it was originally of type `any`.

You can also use type narrowing with union types. For example:
```
let value: number | string = 123;

// Narrow the type of value to string
let valueAsString: string = value as string;

// The narrowed type will be used in the rest of the code
