public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    return (n > 0) && ((n & (n - 1)) == 0) && ((n & 0xFF) == 0xFF) && ((n >> 8) == 0xFF);
}
```

Let's break down the code to understand how it works:

1. `n > 0`: This check is done to exclude negative numbers as powers of 3.
2. `(n & (n - 1)) == 0`: This part checks if the binary representation of `n` has only one set bit. This is a property of powers of 3, where the binary representation has a single set bit shifting to the left.
3. `(n & 0xFF) == 0xFF`: This part checks if the integer is a power of 3 by checking the 8 least significant bits. If it is a power of 3, the 8 least significant bits will be all set to 1.
4. `(n >> 8) == 0xFF`: This part checks if the integer is a power of 3 by checking the next 8 least significant bits shifted to the right. If it's a power of 3, these bits will be all set to 1.

By checking all these conditions, the function can determine whether the given integer `n` is a power of 3 or not, without using any loops or recursion.

Please note that this implementation assumes the input integer `n` is within the constraints specified in the problem, i.e., -2^31 <= n <= 2^31 - 1.

If you want to generalize the function to accept any integer, you can add a null check and a check for zero before the actual condition checks, for example:

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n == 0 || n == null) return false;
    return (n > 0) && ((n & (n - 1)) == 0) && ((n & 0xFF) == 0xFF) && ((n >> 8) == 0xFF);
